Project - AllLife Bank Customer Segmentation¶

Context:¶

  • AllLife Bank wants to focus on its credit card customer base in the next financial year. They have been advised by their marketing research team, that the penetration in the market can be improved.

  • Based on this input, the Marketing team proposes to run personalized campaigns to target new customers as well as upsell to existing customers. Another insight from the market research was that the customers perceive the support services of the back poorly.

  • Based on this, the Operations team wants to upgrade the service delivery model, to ensure that customer queries are resolved faster. Head of Marketing and Head of Delivery both decide to reach out to the Data Science team for help.

Objective:¶

  • The objective of this project is to identify different segments in the existing customer, based on their spending patterns as well as past interaction with the bank, using clustering algorithms, and provide recommendations to the bank on how to better market to and service these customers.

  • Following are the Key questions to be solved:

    1. Identify the different segments in the existing customer base
    2. Identify opportunities to better the services to the Customer
    3. Identify opportunities to expand the Cardit card customer base

Data Information¶

  • The data provided is of various customers of a bank and their financial attributes like credit limit, the total number of credit cards the customer has, and different channels through which customers have contacted the bank for any queries (including visiting the bank, online and through a call center).

  • The detailed data dictionary is given below:

Customer Details

  • Sl_No: Primary key of the records
  • Customer Key: Customer identification number
  • Average Credit Limit: Average credit limit of each customer for all credit cards
  • Total credit cards: Total number of credit cards possessed by the customer
  • Total visits bank: Total number of visits that customer made (yearly) personally to the bank
  • Total visits online: Total number of visits or online logins made by the customer (yearly)
  • Total calls made: Total number of calls made by the customer to the bank or its customer service department (yearly)

Summary of Data Analysis¶

Click to return to TOC

Data Structure:

  • The Dataset contains 660 rows of Customer information and 7 attributes of data
  • All the columns were of int64(7) category in the dataset

Data Cleaning:

  • Sl. No attribute is not required and the column was dropped
  • Customer Key has few repeated Customers which probably was due to changes in the Customer information. Considering the information would be required information, these duplicates Customer information were not dropped
  • Customer Key attribute is not required and the column was dropped
  • There are no missing values and the data were of proper values which doesnt require any formatting
  • Post dropping the above mentioned columns, there were 11 duplicates rows of information which was dropped
  • Post cleanup, there were 649 row samples and 5 feature attributes of the customer information retained.

Data Description:

  • The Customer's average credit limit seems to be distributed and ranges from a min. of 3,000 to max. of 200,000 with an average mean of 34,574. 50% of the customers are having credit limit in the range of 18,000
  • Most of the Customers have atleast 4 credit cards, followed by customers with 6 & 7 credit cards
  • Customers have visited the banks at least 2 times, ranging between 0-5. There are also customers who have not visited even once to the bank
  • Similarly, Customers have visited online system at least 2 times, ranging between 0-15 times. There are also customers who have not visited the online portal even once
  • The number of calls made by the customer to the bank or its customer service department (yearly) are in the range of 0 to 10.
  • Most of the Customers have atleast made 4 calls in a year. There are also customers who have not made any calls even once and this category seems to be second highest

# function to create labeled barplots


def labeled_barplot(data, feature, perc=False, n=None, hueCol=None):
    """
    Barplot with percentage at the top

    data: dataframe
    feature: dataframe column
    perc: whether to display percentages instead of count (default is False)
    n: displays the top n category levels (default is None, i.e., display all levels)
    """

    total = len(data[feature])  # length of the column
    count = data[feature].nunique()
    if n is None:
        plt.figure(figsize=(count + 1, 5))
    else:
        plt.figure(figsize=(n + 1, 7))

    plt.xticks(rotation=90, fontsize=15)

    ax = sns.countplot(
        data=data,
        x=feature,
        palette="Paired",
        hue=hueCol,
        order=data[feature].value_counts().index[:n].sort_values(),
    )

    for p in ax.patches:
        if perc == True:
            label = "{:.1f}%".format(
                100 * p.get_height() / total
            )  # percentage of each class of the category
        else:
            label = p.get_height()  # count of each level of the category

        x = p.get_x() + p.get_width() / 2  # width of the plot
        y = p.get_height()  # height of the plot

        ax.annotate(
            label,
            (x, y),
            ha="center",
            va="center",
            size=12,
            xytext=(0, 5),
            textcoords="offset points",
        )
        # annotate the percentage

    plt.show()  # show the plot

def stacked_barplot(data, predictor, target):
    """
    Print the category counts and plot a stacked bar chart

    data: dataframe
    predictor: independent variable
    target: target variable
    """
    count = data[predictor].nunique()
    sorter = data[target].value_counts().index[-1]
    tab1 = pd.crosstab(data[predictor], data[target], margins=True,).sort_values(
        by=sorter, ascending=False
    )
    print("-" * 30, " Volume ", "-" * 30)
    print(tab1)

    tab1 = pd.crosstab(
        data[predictor], data[target], margins=True, normalize="index"
    ).sort_values(by=sorter, ascending=False)
    print("-" * 30, " Percentage % ", "-" * 30)
    print(tab1)
    print("-" * 120)
    tab = pd.crosstab(data[predictor], data[target], normalize="index").sort_values(
        by=sorter, ascending=False
    )
    tab.plot(kind="bar", stacked=True, figsize=(count + 5, 5))
    plt.legend(
        loc="lower left", frameon=False,
    )
    plt.legend(loc="upper left", bbox_to_anchor=(1, 1))
    plt.show()

# Creating a common function to draw a Boxplot & a Histogram for each of the analysis
def histogram_boxplot(data, feature, figsize=(15, 7), kde=True, bins=None):
    f2, (ax_box2, ax_hist2) = plt.subplots(
        nrows=2,  # Number of rows of the subplot grid= 2
        sharex=True,  # x-axis will be shared among all subplots
        gridspec_kw={"height_ratios": (0.25, 0.75)},
        figsize=figsize,
    )  # creating the 2 subplots

    sns.boxplot(
        data=data, x=feature, ax=ax_box2, showmeans=True, color="violet"
    )  # boxplot will be created and a star will indicate the mean value of the column

    if bins:
        sns.histplot(
            data=data, x=feature, kde=kde, ax=ax_hist2, bins=bins, palette="winter"
        )
    else:
        sns.histplot(data=data, x=feature, kde=kde, ax=ax_hist2)  # For histogram

    ax_hist2.axvline(
        data[feature].mean(), color="green", linestyle="--"
    )  # Add mean to the histogram

    ax_hist2.axvline(
        data[feature].median(), color="black", linestyle="-"
    )  # Add median to the histogram

# functions to treat outliers by flooring and capping


def treat_outliers(df, col, lower=0.25, upper=0.75, mul=1.5):
    """
    Treats outliers in a variable

    df: dataframe
    col: dataframe column
    """
    Q1 = df[col].quantile(lower)  # 25th quantile
    Q3 = df[col].quantile(upper)  # 75th quantile
    IQR = Q3 - Q1
    Lower_Whisker = Q1 - (mul * IQR)
    Upper_Whisker = Q3 + (mul * IQR)

    # all the values smaller than Lower_Whisker will be assigned the value of Lower_Whisker
    # all the values greater than Upper_Whisker will be assigned the value of Upper_Whisker
    df[col] = np.clip(df[col], Lower_Whisker, Upper_Whisker)

    return df


def treat_outliers_all(df, col_list, lower=0.25, upper=0.75, mul=1.5):
    """
    Treat outliers in a list of variables

    df: dataframe
    col_list: list of dataframe columns
    """
    for c in col_list:
        df = treat_outliers(df, c, lower, upper, mul)

    return df

Insights from Data¶

Click to return to TOC

Observations:

  • Avg_Credit_Limit:

    • The credit limit seems to be distributed with avg. limit varying at all levels. The average credit limits is 34,878 and ranges between 3000 to 200000.
    • 4.9% of the customers have 8K credit limit which seems to be the most, followed by 6K (4.6%) & 13K (4.3%) limits.

  • Total_Credit_Cards:

  • The number of credit cards held by the customers are in the range of 1 to 10, with at least 4 credit cards. 50% of the customers have atleast 5 credit cards

    • 22.7% of the customers have 4 cards, followed by 17.4% having 6 cards and 15.4% having 7 cards. There are 2.9% of customers with even 10 cards

  • Total_visits_bank:

    • The number of visits to the bank by the customers are in the range of 0 to 5, with atleast 2 visits in a year. 50% of the customers have visited 2 times, followed by 1 time.
    • 24% of the customers have visited the bank 2 times, followed by 17.3% visiting atleast once. 14.9% of customers have not visited the bank at all in the year

  • Total_visits_online:

    • The number of online visits by the customers are in the range of 0 to 15, with atleast 2 visits in a year. 50% of the Customers have visited 2 times. There are also customers who have not done online logins even once and this category seems to be second highest
    • 28.5% of the customers have made online visits atleast 2 times. 21.7% of customers have not visited the bank at all in the year. There are customers 1.5% of the customers who have visited the bank atleasr 15 times

  • Total_calls_made:

    • The number of calls made by the customer to the bank or its customer service department (yearly) are in the range of 0 to 10. 50% of the Customers have made 4 calls in a year. There are also customers who have not made any calls even once and this category seems to be second highest
    • 16% of the customers have made atleast 4 calls. 14.8% have not made any calls to the bank.

Cluster Analysis - Applying K-means Algorithm¶

Click to return to TOC¶
In [699]:
clusters = range(1, 9)
meanDistortions = []

for k in clusters:
    model = KMeans(n_clusters=k)
    model.fit(subset_scaled_df)
    prediction = model.predict(subset_scaled_df)
    distortion = (
        sum(
            np.min(cdist(subset_scaled_df, model.cluster_centers_, "euclidean"), axis=1)
        )
        / subset_scaled_df.shape[0]
    )

    meanDistortions.append(distortion)

    print("Number of Clusters:", k, "\tAverage Distortion:", distortion)

plt.plot(clusters, meanDistortions, "bx-")
plt.xlabel("k")
plt.ylabel("Average distortion")
plt.title("Selecting k with the Elbow Method")
plt.show()

Using SilhouetteVisualizer to interpret the results¶

Click to return to TOC

Below are the points that is being considered to satisfy selecting the optimal K-value.

  • No negative silhouette coefficent value
  • All Clusters should cross the avg Silhouette score
  • All clusters should have the different variations (width)
  • All clusters should have different Silhouette score

  • Cluster 0:

    • Primarily contains customers with median credit limit of 12,239. It has low credit limit customers
    • Customers with a mean of 2 and with a range of 1-3 cards. Possibly the mid range of customers with cards
    • It contains customers who have not visited the banks or a max of 2 visits. The average visits is 1
    • This cluster Customers have visited online portal only 2-4 times with an average of 3 visits
    • Customers in this group have made the most calls to the bank or Customer center with a range between 5-9 calls and on an average, at least 7 times
    • Based on the style analysis, we see this cluster has considered customers with low credit, less number of cards, less visits to the bank and occasionally visiting the online portal and making a lot of calls to the bank or service department
    • Possiblities are that this customers have very low credit limit & cards and they are making a lot of enquiries over phone

  • Cluster 1:

    • Primarily contains customers with median credit limit of 34,071. It has medium credit limit customers
    • Customers with a mean of 5 and with a range of 4-6 cards. Possibly the mid range of customers with cards
    • It contains customers who have visited the banks the max number of times - 3 to 5 times. The average visit is 4
    • This cluster Customers have visited online portal only 0-2 times with an average of 1 visit
    • Customers in this group have made the medium number of calls to the bank or Customer center with a range between 1-3 calls and on an average, at least 2 times
    • Based on the style analysis, we see this cluster covers Customers with medium credit, moderate number of cards, high number of visits to bank, least visits to the online portal and making a medium number of calls to the bank or service department

  • Cluster 2:

    • Primarily contains customers with high credit limit of 141,040. It has high credit limit customers
    • Customers with max number of cards ranging from 8-10, min of 9 cards. Possibly the mid range of customers with cards
    • It contains customers who have least visits to the banks, almost zero to 1 visits
    • This cluster Customers have visited online portal most of the time, atleast ten time in the year
    • Customers in this group have made the least number of calls to the bank or Customer center with a range between 0-2 calls and on an average, at least 2 times
    • Based on the style analysis, we see this cluster covers Customers with high credit limits, max number of cards, less visits to bank, most visits to the online portal and making a least number of calls to the bank or service department
    • Possiblities are that this customers are high value customers and very satisifed with the online portal for all information, that they dont have to visit the bank or call customer care for any information

Using Distance Metrics - "chebyshev", "mahalanobis", "cityblock" (Manhattan) & corresponding linkage methods¶

In [721]:
# list of distance metrics
distance_metrics = ["chebyshev", "mahalanobis", "cityblock"]

# list of linkage methods
linkage_methods = ["single", "complete", "average", "weighted"]

compare = []

high_cophenet_corr = 0
high_dm_lm = [0, 0]

for dm in distance_metrics:
    for lm in linkage_methods:
        Z = linkage(subset_scaled_df, metric=dm, method=lm)
        c, coph_dists = cophenet(Z, pdist(subset_scaled_df))
        print(
            "Cophenetic correlation for {} distance and {} linkage is {}.".format(
                dm.capitalize(), lm, c
            )
        )
        if high_cophenet_corr < c:
            high_cophenet_corr = c
            high_dm_lm[0] = dm
            high_dm_lm[1] = lm
            
        compare.append([dm + " - " + lm, c])

Visualizing Dendrograms for different linkage methods using Euclidean metric¶

In [726]:
# list of linkage methods
linkage_methods = ["complete", "average", "centroid", "ward", "weighted"]

# to create a subplot image
fig, axs = plt.subplots(len(linkage_methods), 1, figsize=(15, 40))

# We will enumerate through the list of linkage methods above
# For each linkage method, we will plot the dendrogram and calculate the cophenetic correlation
for i, method in enumerate(linkage_methods):
    Z = linkage(subset_scaled_df, metric="euclidean", method=method)

    dendrogram(Z, ax=axs[i])
    axs[i].set_title(f"Dendrogram ({method.capitalize()} Linkage)")

    coph_corr, coph_dist = cophenet(Z, pdist(subset_scaled_df))
    axs[i].annotate(
        f"Cophenetic\nCorrelation\n{coph_corr:0.2f}",
        (0.80, 0.80),
        xycoords="axes fraction",
    )

Observations

  • The Cophenetic correlation using Euclidean metric is highest for Average, Centroid and Complete linkage methods
  • Comparing the Dendograms of the Euclidean metric, though the Cophenetic Coefficient is low for Ward linkage, we see the Ward linkage to have stable homogenous clusters with more variability and distinct clusters compared with the other linkages
  • 3 seems to be an appropriate number of clusters from the dendogram for Ward linkage

Summary¶

  • Hierarchical Clustering takes a longer time to compute than the K Means technique, especially when the Dendogram has to be rendered. KMeans visualization was more faster
  • Both the techniques provided a wide range of clusters, but HC had more options to validate than KMeans
  • The Segmentation of the data into groups were pretty much the same number & enity values
    • K-Means:
      • K = 2 ==> 0: 221 / 1: 428 /
      • K = 3 ==> 0: 221 / 1: 378 / 2: 50
      • K = 4 ==> 0: 185 / 1: 220 / 2: 50 / 3: 194
      • K = 5 ==> 0: 194 / 1: 185 / 2: 50 / 3: 114 / 4: 106
    • HC:
      • K = 2 ==> 0: 222 / 1: 427 /
      • K = 3 ==> 0: 377 / 1: 222 / 2: 50
      • K = 4 ==> 0: 222 / 1: 195 / 2: 50 / 3: 182
      • K = 5 ==> 0: 182 / 1: 195 / 2: 50 / 3: 102 / 4: 120

With respect to the Cluster outcomes:

  • Based on the cluster analysis done using both K-Means & Hierarchical techniques, we are able to infer that a cluster of 3 would be a good number to group the segments
  • The Cluster profiling of both the techniques provides a similar grouping of the data
  • Looking at the number of entries in each of the groups, we find that it is almost alike except the context of the tagging
    • In K means, we have the low credit limit customers under 0, mid credit limit customers under 1 and the rest in 2
    • In HC, we have the low credit limit customers under 1, mid credit limit customers under 0 and the rest in 2

Insights & Recommendations:¶

Click to return to TOC

Based on the Customer Information:

- The credit limit seems to be distributed with avg. limit varying at all levels. The average credit limits is 34,878 and ranges between 3000 to 200000.
- 4.9% of the customers have 8K credit limit which seems to be the most, followed by 6K (4.6%) & 13K (4.3%) limits. 
- The number of credit cards held by the customers are in the range of 1 to 10, with at least 4 credit cards. 50% of the customers have atleast 5 credit cards
- 22.7% of the customers have 4 cards, followed by 17.4% having 6 cards and 15.4% having 7 cards. There are 2.9% of customers with even 10 cards
- The number of visits to the bank by the customers are in the range of 0 to 5, with atleast 2 visits in a year. 50% of the customers have visited 2 times, followed by 1 time. 
- 24% of the customers have visited the bank 2 times, followed by 17.3% visiting atleast once. 14.9% of customers have not visited the bank at all in the year
- The number of online visits by the customers are in the range of 0 to 15, with atleast 2 visits in a year. 50% of the Customers have visited 2 times. There are also customers who have not done online logins even once and this category seems to be second highest
- 28.5% of the customers have made online visits atleast 2 times. 21.7% of customers have not visited the bank at all in the year. There are customers 1.5% of the customers who have visited the bank atleasr 15 times
- The number of calls made by the customer to the bank or its customer service department (yearly) are in the range of 0 to 10. 50% of the Customers have made 4 calls in a year. There are also customers who have not made any calls even once and this category seems to be second highest
- 16% of the customers have made atleast 4 calls. 14.8% have not made any calls to the bank.



For more Insights from the individual techniques, K - Means Summary & Hierarchical Cluster Summary


Based on the analysis, following are the recommendations:

  • There are significant customers holding less number of credit cards. Banks can focus to market more number of credit cards to the Customers
  • Customers with more credit cards have less visits to the bank or calls made. It could be that they have already applied for all cards and happy with the services, that they dont need further information. By making the customers subscribe for more cards, the number of calls made or bank visits can be reduced
  • One of the obsevation is Customers who have made visits to the bank have high number of calls made. It could be that customers are calling the bank for a followup based on their visits or pending queries. The Call processing system needs to be enhanced so that the number of visits to the bank & the calls made reduces
  • Customers with low credit limit and less numbers of cards seem to be making a lot of calls to the bank. It could be that they are enquiring about the other cards of the bank. By improving the call processing system, most of the enquiries can be converted into a successful transaction
  • Another observations is Customers using the online system, seems to have less visits to the bank and also made very less number of calls. It means the Bank online system is robust and provides most the details required by the customer without a bank visit or calls. The Bank should look at making their customers utilize the online system more
